# Asynchronous FIFO (Verilog)

## Overview

This project implements a parameterized Asynchronous FIFO (First-In First-Out) in Verilog HDL. Unlike a synchronous FIFO, the write and read operations are performed using two independent clock domains, making it suitable for Clock Domain Crossing (CDC) applications.

The design uses Gray code pointers and two-stage synchronizers to safely transfer pointer information between the write and read clock domains while minimizing the risk of metastability.

---

## Features

- Parameterized Data Width
- Parameterized FIFO Depth
- Independent Read and Write Clocks
- Binary and Gray Code Pointers
- Two-Flip-Flop Pointer Synchronizers
- Clock Domain Crossing (CDC) Support
- Full and Empty Status Flags
- Simultaneous Read and Write Support
- Fully Synthesizable RTL
- Comprehensive Testbench

---

## Why Asynchronous FIFO?

In many digital systems, data is transferred between modules operating at different clock frequencies.

Examples include:

- CPU to UART
- ADC to Processor
- FPGA to External Memory
- Different clock domains inside an SoC

Directly transferring multi-bit signals between asynchronous clock domains may result in metastability and incorrect data interpretation.

An Asynchronous FIFO provides a reliable mechanism for transferring data safely between two unrelated clock domains.

---

## FIFO Architecture

The FIFO consists of the following blocks:

- Memory Array
- Binary Write Pointer
- Binary Read Pointer
- Gray Write Pointer
- Gray Read Pointer
- Write Pointer Synchronizer
- Read Pointer Synchronizer
- Full Detection Logic
- Empty Detection Logic

The binary pointers are used for memory addressing, while the Gray pointers are synchronized across clock domains for reliable full and empty detection.

---

## Parameters

| Parameter | Description | Default |
|-----------|-------------|---------|
| DATA_WIDTH | Width of each data word | 8 |
| DEPTH | FIFO Depth (Power of Two) | 16 |

---

## Module Interface

### Inputs

| Signal | Width | Description |
|---------|-------|-------------|
| wr_clk | 1 | Write Clock |
| rd_clk | 1 | Read Clock |
| rst | 1 | Active High Reset |
| wr_en | 1 | Write Enable |
| rd_en | 1 | Read Enable |
| data_in | DATA_WIDTH | Input Data |

### Outputs

| Signal | Width | Description |
|---------|-------|-------------|
| data_out | DATA_WIDTH | Output Data |
| full | 1 | FIFO Full Indicator |
| empty | 1 | FIFO Empty Indicator |

---

## Design Methodology

### Binary Pointers

Binary pointers are used for:

- Memory Addressing
- Pointer Increment Operations

---

### Gray Pointers

Gray pointers are generated using:

```verilog
gray = binary ^ (binary >> 1);
```

Only one bit changes between consecutive Gray code values, making them suitable for clock domain crossing.

---

### Two-Flip-Flop Synchronizers

Gray pointers are synchronized across clock domains using two cascaded flip-flops.

This significantly reduces the probability of metastability propagating into the receiving logic.

---

### Empty Detection

The FIFO is empty when the synchronized write Gray pointer equals the next read Gray pointer.

---

### Full Detection

The FIFO is full when:

- The lower Gray pointer bits match.
- The two most significant Gray bits are inverted.

This corresponds to the binary condition where:

- Address bits are equal.
- Wrap-around bit is different.

---

## Testbench Verification

The testbench verifies:

- Reset Operation
- Independent Read and Write Clocks
- Single Write
- Single Read
- Multiple Writes
- Multiple Reads
- FIFO Full Condition
- FIFO Empty Condition
- Write When Full
- Read When Empty
- Different Read/Write Clock Frequencies
- Pointer Synchronization Across Clock Domains

Simulation confirms correct FIFO operation under asynchronous clock conditions.

